emissions\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, produced both directly and indirectly to meet the requirements of an individual, an organization or a population.\u003csup\u003e(1)\u003c/sup\u003eIt is usually calculated as an equivalent of carbon dioxide (CO2) in tons. Carbon footprint is one of the elements of \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency/ecological-footprint\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eecological footprint\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, a concept developed in the 1990s by Canadian ecologists William Rees and Mathis Wackernagel, to estimate the environmental resources that a population consumes.\u003csup\u003e(2,3)\u003c/sup\u003e \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability#lifecycle-assessment-lca\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eLife-cycle assessment (LCA)\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003emethods also enable the measurement of the carbon footprint of manufactured products. It must be noted that there are vast differences in ecological footprint between different countries and also between different social groups within countries, which is a reflection of \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency/global-inequality\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eglobal inequality\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSee also: \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency/carbon-neutral\"\u003eCarbon neutral\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency/decarbonization\"\u003eDecarbonization\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency/carbon-offsetting\"\u003eCarbon offsetting\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency/fossil-fuels\"\u003eFossil fuels\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency/climate-change\"\u003eClimate change\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency/global-warming\