uct developers guidance for meeting the principles of circular design. Examples include \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/zero-waste-design\"\u003e\u003ci\u003ezero waste design\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, design for longevity, modular design, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/design-for-disassembly\"\u003e\u003ci\u003edesign for disassembly\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, design for remanufacture, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/upcycling\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eupcycling\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, design for \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/recyclability\"\u003e\u003ci\u003erecyclability\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e or design for biodegradability.\u003csup\u003e(2)\u003c/sup\u003eHowever, it is critical to recognize that circular design can only bring its intended environmental benefits if it is accompanied by fundamental cuts in global production and \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/consumption\"\u003e\u003ci\u003econsumption\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e rates, radically slowing down the overall throughput of materials and resources across all industries.\u003csup\u003e(3-5)\u003c/sup\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSee also: \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/environmental-impacts-of-fashion/efficiency\"\u003eEfficiency\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/closed-loop-recycling\"\u003eClosed-loop recycling\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/downcycling\"\u003eDowncycling\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/end-of-life\"\u003eEnd of life\u003c/a\u00