 which comes from \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/environmental-impacts-of-fashion#packaging\"\u003e\u003ci\u003epackaging\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, catering for the lifestyles of high-income countries such as the United States, Australia and the countries of the European Union. The United Nation’s review of 192 countries showed that as of July 2018, 127 countries introduced some kind of regulation of plastic bags (in some cases going back to the 2000s), 27 now regulate either selected single-use plastic products (e.g. plates, cups or straws) or have limits on their production levels, and 8 countries have laws that control the use and manufacture of plastic microbeads in personal care and detergents.\u003csup\u003e(3)\u003c/sup\u003e Yet, to truly address the alarming impacts of global plastic pollution, we need more systemic, long-term solutions that will corrode the throwaway mindset and the market logic that enables unlimited manufacture of materials and products that pose serious risks to human health and the environment.\u003csup\u003e(1-7)\u003c/sup\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSee also: \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency#global-inequality\"\u003eGlobal inequality\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/environmental-impacts-of-fashion#microfiber-pollution\"\u003eMicrofiber pollution\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/environmental-impacts-of-fashion#waste\"\u003eWaste\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/waste-classification\"\u003eWaste classification\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/environmental-impacts-of-fashion#take-make-use-dispose-model\"\u003eTake-make-use-dispose model\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability#circular-economy\"\u003eCircular Economy\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca 