ts.\u003csup\u003e(1,2)\u003c/sup\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSee also: \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/closed-loop-recycling\"\u003eClosed-loop recycling\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","references":null,"hideFromFeed":false,"createdAt":"2023-10-09T00:23:28.956Z","updatedAt":"2023-10-09T00:23:47.613Z","publishedAt":"2023-02-23T12:49:19.215Z","locale":"en"},{"id":4128,"title":"4.10 Tools, resources and frameworks","slug":"tools-resources-and-frameworks","text":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"color:rgb(45,46,47);\"\u003eThe following section helps to signpost readers to external tools, resources and frameworks that focus on fashion and sustainability. This is not an exhaustive list, and terms will continue to be added on a regular basis. Inclusion here does not constitute an endorsement from any of the co-authors of the Glossary.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","references":null,"hideFromFeed":true,"createdAt":"2023-10-09T00:23:49.981Z","updatedAt":"2023-10-09T00:24:08.120Z","publishedAt":"2023-02-23T13:26:18.905Z","locale":"en"},{"id":4137,"title":"4.8 Policy","slug":"policy","text":null,"references":null,"hideFromFeed":true,"createdAt":"2023-10-09T00:24:10.515Z","updatedAt":"2023-10-09T00:24:33.236Z","publishedAt":"2023-02-23T13:14:45.428Z","locale":"en"},{"id":4200,"title":"Flax","slug":"flax","text":"\u003cp style=\"margin-left:0px;\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/linen\"\u003eSee Linen\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","references":null,"hideFromFeed":false,"createdAt":"2023-10-09T00:25:33.303Z","updatedAt":"2023-10-09T00:25:51.294Z","publishedAt":"2023-02-23T12:49:35.329Z","locale":"en"},{"id":4227,"title":"Post-growth fashion","slug":"post-growth-fashion","text":"\u003cp\u003ePost-growth fashion is a new narrative of fashion that offers an alternative to the market-driven \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/environmental-impacts-of-fashion#overconsumption\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eoverconsumption\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003eby focusing instead on the agency and satisfaction that people draw from care and long-term use of familiar clothes. Post-growth fashion draws on the \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/post-growth-economy\"\u003e\u003ci\u003epost-growth economy\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/craft-of-use\"\u003e\u003ci\u003ecraft of use\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, both recognizing that neither economy nor fashion are isolated systems. They cannot exist outside the limits set by \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/climate-emergency/planetary-boundaries\"\u003e\u003ci\u003eplanetary boundaries\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e or without a connection to people. Post-growth fashion values everyday, informal, and resourceful ways of engaging with clothes, where close connections between making, re-making and use enable richer experiences and more \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/sustainable-fashion\"\u003e\u003ci\u003esustainable fashion\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003efutures.\u003csup\u003e(1)\u003c/sup\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSee also: \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/localism\"\u003eLocalism\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/paradigm-change\"\u003eParadigm change\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/systems-change\"\u003eSystems change\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability#interdependence\"\u003eInterdependence\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashi