ed manually by the process of shredding. This results in shorter fibers and lower-quality yarn. Non-virgin fibers are therefore mostly blended with virgin fibers to balance the quality of the final material. 100% non-virgin materials are still relatively rare.\u003csup\u003e(1-5)\u003c/sup\u003e (NB: Valid at the time of writing, December 2019)\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSee also: \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/virgin-materials\"\u003eVirgin materials\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/recyclability\"\u003eRecyclability\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/blend-materials\"\u003eBlend materials\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/mono-materials\"\u003eMono materials\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/nylon\"\u003eNylon\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/closed-loop-recycling\"\u003eClosed-loop recycling\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/key-elements-of-fashion-and-sustainability/circular-economy\"\u003eCircular economy\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.condenast.com/glossary/social-cultural-and-economic-impacts-of-fashion/greenwashing\"\u003eGreenwashing\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","references":"\u003col\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.ellenmacarthurfoundation.org/assets/downloads/publications/A-New-Textiles-Economy_Full-Report_Updated_1-12-17.pdf\"\u003eEllen MacArthur Foundation (2017). A New Textiles Economy: Redesigning Fashion’s Future.\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://op.europa.eu/en/publication-detail/-/publication/43511a04-b988-11e9-9d01-01aa75ed71a1\"\u003e